"Cerri C.E.P., Coleman K., Jenkinson D.S., Bernoux M., Victoria R., Cerri C.C.","Modeling Soil Carbon from Forest and Pasture Ecosystems of Amazon, Brazil",2003,"Soil Science Society of America Journal","67","6",,"1879","1887",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0242424110&partnerID=40&md5=310f825695623c67a40a8aa06a8d9820","Ctro. de Ener. Nucl. na Agricultura, Universidade de São Paulo, CP.96. Piracicaba, Brazil; Agric. and the Environment Division, IACR-Rothamsted, Harpenden, Hertfordshire AL5 2JQ, United Kingdom","Cerri, C.E.P., Ctro. de Ener. Nucl. na Agricultura, Universidade de São Paulo, CP.96. Piracicaba, Brazil; Coleman, K., Agric. and the Environment Division, IACR-Rothamsted, Harpenden, Hertfordshire AL5 2JQ, United Kingdom; Jenkinson, D.S., Agric. and the Environment Division, IACR-Rothamsted, Harpenden, Hertfordshire AL5 2JQ, United Kingdom; Bernoux, M.; Victoria, R., Ctro. de Ener. Nucl. na Agricultura, Universidade de São Paulo, CP.96. Piracicaba, Brazil; Cerri, C.C., Ctro. de Ener. Nucl. na Agricultura, Universidade de São Paulo, CP.96. Piracicaba, Brazil","Conversion of tropical forest to agricultural management has important implications for C storage in soils and global climate change. The Nova Vida Ranch in the Western Brazilian Amazon basin provided a unique opportunity to study the conversion of tropical forests to pastures established in 1989, 1587, 1583, 1979, 1572, 1551, and 1911, in comparison with uncleared forest. Soils were analyzed for organic C, bulk density, total N, pH, clay content, and biomass C. The forest soil contained 34 Mg C ha-1 in the 0- to 30-cm layer: modeling clearance and conversion to pasture caused an initial fall in the C stock, followed by a slow rise. After 88 yr, the pasture soil contained 53% more C than the forest soil. The increase in total N on conversion to pasture was less marked, which led to C/N ratios in the pasture soils being higher than in the forest soil. The Rothamsted C turnover model (RothC-26.3) was used to simulate changes hi the 0- to 10- and 0- to 30-cm layer of soils when forest was converted to pasture. The model predicted that conversion to pasture would cause a 54% increase in the stock of organic C in the top 30 cm of soil in 100 yr. The modeled input of plant C to the 0- to 30-cm layer of soil under pasture was assumed to be 8.28 Mg C ha-1 yr-1. The model provided a reasonable estimate of the microbial biomass (BIO) C in the 0- to 10-cm soil layer. This was an independent test of model performance, because no adjustments were made to the model to generate output.",,"Biomass; Carbon; Climate change; Ecosystems; Forestry; Forest soils; Soil testing; carbon sequestration; forest soil; modeling; pasture; soil carbon; soil nitrogen; Brazil",,,,,,"Anderson, J.M., Ingram, J.S.I., (1989) Tropical Soil Biology and Fertility: A Handbook of Methods, , CAB International, Wallingford, UK; Bastos, T.X., Diniz, A.S., Avaliação do clima do Estado de Rondônia para desenvolvimento agrícola (1982) Boletim de Pesquisa No 44, , Belém, EMBRAPA-CPATU; Batjes, N.H., Sombroek, W.G., Possibilities for C sequestration in tropical and subtropical soils (1997) Global Change Biology, 3, pp. 161-173; Bernoux, M., Arrouays, D., Cerri, C.C., Graça, P.M.D.A., Volkoff, B., Trichet, J., Estimation des stocks de carbone des sols du Rondônia (Amazonie brésilienne) (1998) Études et Gestion des Sols, 5, pp. 31-42. , In French; Bernoux, M., Arrouays, D., Cerri, C.C., Volkoff, B., Jolivet, C., Bulk density of Brazilian Amazon soils related to other soil properties (1998) Soil Sci. Soc. Am. J., 62, pp. 743-749; Boddey, R.M., Rao, I.M., Thomas, R.J., Nutrient cycling and environmental impacts of Brachiaria pastures (1996) Brachiaria: Biology, Agronomy and Improvement, pp. 72-86. , J.L. Miles et al. CIAT, Cali, Colombia; Bonde, T.A., Christensen, B.T., Cerri, C.C., Dynamics of soil organic matter as reflected by natural 13C abundance in particle size fractions of forested and 